  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>How SAT Scoring Works</h2>
    <p>The SAT, administered by the College Board, is one of the two major standardized tests used for college admissions in the United States. Since the transition to the digital SAT in 2024, the test structure has changed significantly, but the scoring scale remains the same: 400 to 1600 total points, with two section scores of 200 to 800 each.</p>
    <p>The digital SAT consists of two sections: <strong>Reading and Writing</strong> and <strong>Math</strong>. The Reading and Writing section contains 54 questions, while the Math section contains 44 questions. Both sections use a multistage adaptive testing format, meaning the difficulty of your second module depends on how well you performed on the first module within each section.</p>
    <p>Your <strong>raw score</strong> is simply the number of questions you answer correctly. There is no penalty for incorrect answers on the digital SAT, so you should always guess rather than leave a question blank. Your raw score is then converted to a <strong>scaled score</strong> between 200 and 800 for each section through a process called equating.</p>
    <p>Equating adjusts for slight differences in difficulty between different test forms administered on different dates. This means a raw score of 40 on one test date might convert to a slightly different scaled score than a raw score of 40 on another date. The conversion tables used in this calculator are approximate averages based on publicly available score data.</p>

    <h2>Understanding SAT Score Ranges</h2>
    <p>SAT scores fall into distinct ranges that generally correspond to different levels of college selectivity. Understanding where your score falls can help you build a balanced college list with reach, match, and safety schools.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table class="info-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Score Range</th><th>Level</th><th>Percentile (approx.)</th><th>School Type</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1400&ndash;1600</td><td>Highly Competitive</td><td>95th&ndash;99th+</td><td>Ivy League, Stanford, MIT, top 20 schools</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1200&ndash;1399</td><td>Competitive</td><td>75th&ndash;94th</td><td>Selective state flagships, top 50 private schools</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1000&ndash;1199</td><td>Average</td><td>40th&ndash;74th</td><td>Most state universities, many private colleges</td></tr>
          <tr><td>800&ndash;999</td><td>Below Average</td><td>10th&ndash;39th</td><td>Less selective schools, community college transfers</td></tr>
          <tr><td>400&ndash;799</td><td>Needs Improvement</td><td>1st&ndash;9th</td><td>Open admission schools, may benefit from retesting</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The national average SAT score is approximately 1050, meaning a score above 1050 puts you in the upper half of all test takers. However, the average score at your target college may be significantly higher or lower than this national figure. Always research the middle 50 percent score range (25th to 75th percentile) for admitted students at each school on your list.</p>

    <h2>What Colleges Expect</h2>
    <p>College admissions is a holistic process, and SAT scores are just one component of your application. However, standardized test scores remain an important factor at most institutions, even as some schools have adopted test-optional policies. Understanding what different types of colleges expect can help you set realistic score goals.</p>
    <p><strong>Highly selective institutions</strong> (acceptance rates below 15 percent) typically see middle 50 percent SAT ranges of 1450 to 1570. Schools like Harvard, Princeton, MIT, Stanford, and Caltech attract the highest-scoring applicants. Even at these schools, however, a perfect SAT score does not guarantee admission — they evaluate the entire application holistically.</p>
    <p><strong>Selective universities</strong> (acceptance rates of 15 to 40 percent) typically have middle 50 percent ranges of 1250 to 1450. This includes many well-known private universities and the most competitive public universities. Strong scores in this range, combined with good grades and extracurriculars, make you a competitive applicant.</p>
    <p><strong>Moderately selective schools</strong> (acceptance rates of 40 to 70 percent) often have middle 50 percent ranges of 1050 to 1250. Most state universities fall into this category. A score in or above this range, combined with a solid GPA, gives you a good chance of admission.</p>
    <p><strong>Less selective and open-admission schools</strong> may have no minimum SAT requirement or accept students with scores below 1000. Community colleges typically do not require SAT scores for admission but may use them for placement into courses.</p>

    <h2>SAT Score Comparison Table by Selectivity Tier</h2>
    <p>The following table shows approximate SAT score expectations for different tiers of colleges. Use these ranges to evaluate where your score positions you relative to admitted students at various school types.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table class="info-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>College Tier</th><th>Examples</th><th>25th Percentile SAT</th><th>75th Percentile SAT</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Most Selective</td><td>Harvard, MIT, Stanford</td><td>1500</td><td>1570</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Highly Selective</td><td>Georgetown, USC, NYU</td><td>1370</td><td>1510</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Very Selective</td><td>U of Michigan, UVA, UNC</td><td>1300</td><td>1470</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Selective</td><td>Penn State, Ohio State, U of Florida</td><td>1200</td><td>1390</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Moderately Selective</td><td>Arizona State, U of Oregon</td><td>1080</td><td>1290</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Less Selective</td><td>Many regional universities</td><td>950</td><td>1150</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>SAT vs. ACT</h2>
    <p>The SAT and ACT are both widely accepted for college admissions, and most students perform comparably on both tests. However, there are meaningful differences in format, content, and pacing that may make one test a better fit for your strengths.</p>
    <p>The <strong>SAT</strong> has two sections (Reading and Writing, Math) with 98 total questions and is scored 400 to 1600. The digital format uses adaptive testing, and students generally have more time per question than on the ACT. The math section allows a calculator throughout, and the reading passages tend to be slightly shorter in the digital format.</p>
    <p>The <strong>ACT</strong> has four sections (English, Math, Reading, Science) with 215 total questions and is scored 1 to 36 (composite average of section scores). The ACT is known for its faster pacing — students must answer more questions in less time. The ACT also includes a science reasoning section that tests data interpretation, experimental design, and conflicting viewpoints, which has no equivalent on the SAT.</p>
    <p>To determine which test is better for you, take a timed practice test of each under realistic conditions and compare your scores. College Board and ACT both provide free official practice tests. Many students find they prefer one format over the other, and since all US colleges accept both tests equally, you should take the one on which you score higher.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table class="info-table">
