    <h2>Test Prep Tips for the Digital SAT</h2>
    <p>Effective SAT preparation can significantly improve your score. Research suggests that dedicated test prep typically raises scores by 100 to 200 points, with some students seeing even larger gains. Here are evidence-based strategies for maximizing your SAT performance.</p>
    <p><strong>Take a diagnostic test first.</strong> Before you begin studying, take a full-length official practice test under timed conditions. This establishes your baseline score and helps you identify which content areas and question types need the most work. The College Board offers free digital practice tests through Bluebook, its official testing app.</p>
    <p><strong>Focus on your weakest areas.</strong> After analyzing your diagnostic test, identify the specific question types where you lost the most points. Targeted practice on your weakest areas yields the highest score gains. If you missed most of the algebra questions but got nearly all the reading questions right, spend more time on math practice than reading practice.</p>
    <p><strong>Learn the test format.</strong> The digital SAT uses a multistage adaptive format. Understanding how the test works — that your first module performance determines the difficulty of your second module — can help you approach the test strategically. Prioritize accuracy on the first module, as performing well there gives you access to the higher-scoring second module.</p>
    <p><strong>Practice with official materials.</strong> Official College Board practice tests and questions are the most accurate representation of what you will see on test day. Third-party materials can be helpful for additional practice, but they may not perfectly match the style and difficulty of real SAT questions. Khan Academy's free SAT prep, developed in partnership with the College Board, is an excellent free resource.</p>
    <p><strong>Build math fundamentals.</strong> The SAT Math section tests algebra, problem-solving and data analysis, advanced math, and geometry. If you struggle with foundational concepts like linear equations, ratios, or percent problems, review these topics before attempting full practice tests. A strong foundation makes complex problems much more approachable.</p>
    <p><strong>Develop reading strategies.</strong> For the Reading and Writing section, practice active reading — annotating passages, identifying main ideas, and recognizing evidence-based conclusions. The digital SAT uses shorter passages than the old paper test, but you still need to comprehend text quickly and accurately. Time management is critical: do not spend too long on any single question.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How is the SAT scored?</summary>
        <p>The digital SAT is scored on a scale of 400 to 1600. It has two sections: Reading and Writing (200-800) and Math (200-800). Your raw score (number of correct answers) is converted to a scaled score using an equating process that accounts for slight differences in difficulty between test forms. There is no penalty for wrong answers, so you should always answer every question even if you need to guess.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is a good SAT score for college admissions?</summary>
        <p>A "good" SAT score depends entirely on your target schools. The national average is around 1050. A score of 1200 or above (roughly top 25 percent) is competitive for most state universities. Highly selective schools typically expect 1400 or higher. Research the middle 50 percent score range for admitted students at your target schools to set an appropriate personal goal.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Should I take the SAT or ACT?</summary>
        <p>All US colleges accept both tests equally. The best test for you depends on your strengths. The SAT emphasizes analytical reasoning and gives more time per question, while the ACT includes a science section and moves at a faster pace with more questions. Take a practice test of each under timed conditions and compare your scores. Many students score comparably on both, but some find one format significantly easier.</p>
      </details>
    </div>

